Step 1 — One Packet → 9 Tokens (Concrete Example)
Take a real packet from your Wednesday PCAP (DoS attack):


Raw packet fields (from Scapy, NO payload):
  ip.src   = 192.168.1.5      ip.dst  = 192.168.1.100
  ip.ttl   = 118              ip.proto = 6 (TCP)
  tcp.sport = 49451           tcp.dport = 80
  tcp.flags = 0x10 (ACK)
  frame.len = 1460            timestamp = 1492177940.123
  last_ts   = 1492177940.089  → Δt = 0.034s
_pkt_to_tokens() converts this to exactly 9 integers:


token[0] = DIR_C2S        = 9    # src matches flow origin → client→server
token[1] = LEN_BIN_28     = 39   # log1p(1460) → falls in bin 28, offset 11 → ID=39
token[2] = DT_BIN_15      = 78   # log1p(0.034) → bin 15, offset 43 → ID=58+15=73
token[3] = TTL_BIN_4      = 87   # TTL=118 → bin 4 of 16, offset 75 → ID=79
token[4] = PROTO_TCP      = 5    # fixed token
token[5] = SPORT_H_11     = 102  # 49451 % 64 = 11, offset 91 → ID=102
token[6] = DPORT_H_16     = 171  # 80 % 64 = 16, offset 155 → ID=171
token[7] = FLAG_ACK       = 215  # ACK flag, offset 219 → ID=223
token[8] = PKT_SEP        = 3    # fixed separator
Key point: The payload bytes (GET /index.php, HTTP content) are never touched. Only header integers are read.

Step 2 — One Flow → Token Sequence
A Wednesday DoS flow has 500 packets (before truncation at 128):


Flow: 192.168.1.5:49451 → 192.168.1.100:80  (TCP, DoS Hulk)

Sequence built by _build_sequence():

Position:  0    1-9           10-18          19-27    ...   1153  1154
Token:    [BOS][pkt1: 9 toks][pkt2: 9 toks][pkt3...] ... [pkt128][EOS]

Actual IDs: [1, 9,39,73,79,5,102,171,223,3,  10,41,68,79,5,171,102,224,3,  ...]
              ↑  ↑  ↑  ↑  ↑ ↑  ↑   ↑   ↑  ↑
             BOS DIR LEN DT TTL P  SP  DP FLAG SEP

Total length = 1 + 128×9 + 1 = 1,154 tokens
Step 3 — Batching (Variable Length → Padded Tensor)
Flows have different lengths. pcap_collate_lm pads each batch:


# A batch of 4 flows with lengths [38, 1154, 92, 245]
# After padding to max length in batch (1154):

tensor shape: (4, 1154)

[1, 9,39,73,... , 2,  0,  0,  0, ...]   # flow 1: len=38,  rest=PAD(0)
[1, 9,41,68,... , 2]                     # flow 2: len=1154, no padding needed
[1,10,28,55,... , 2,  0,  0,  0, ...]   # flow 3: len=92,  rest=PAD(0)
[1, 9,33,71,... , 2,  0,  0,  0, ...]   # flow 4: len=245, rest=PAD(0)
The PLM ignores PAD tokens via ignore_index=PAD_ID in the cross-entropy loss.

Step 4a — Training (Parallel, Teacher-Forced)
The full sequence goes through all RWKV blocks in one forward pass:


input_ids  = token_ids[:, :-1]   # [BOS, pkt1..., pkt127]   shape (B, T-1)
target_ids = token_ids[:, 1:]    # [pkt1..., pkt128, EOS]   shape (B, T-1)

                    ┌──────────────────────────────┐
input_ids ──────→   │  Embedding (B,T,256)         │
                    │  RWKV Block 1 (TimeMix+ChanMix)│
                    │  RWKV Block 2                 │
                    │  ...                          │
                    │  RWKV Block 6                 │
                    │  LayerNorm                    │
                    │  LM Head (B,T,vocab=227)      │
                    └──────────────────────────────┘
                              │
                    cross_entropy(logits, target_ids)
                              │
                         LM Loss → backprop
What the model learns in Phase 1:

"After seeing DIR_C2S + LEN_BIN_28 (large packet) + DT_BIN_15 (fast), the next token is very likely DIR_C2S again (not DIR_S2C) — because DoS flows are one-directional."

A DoS flow violates this grammar → high perplexity.

Step 4b — Inference (Streaming, Token-by-Token)
For live/offline scoring, the model runs one token at a time using model.step():


# For each incoming packet in a live flow:

states = model.init_states(batch=1, device)   # zero RWKV hidden state

for token_id in flow_token_sequence:
    logits, states = model.step(token_id, states)
    #                           ↑                ↑
    #                   current token      updated RWKV state
    #                                      (carried to next pkt)

    log_prob = F.log_softmax(logits)[next_token_id]
    nll += -log_prob          # accumulate NLL

perplexity = exp(nll / n_tokens)   # high = anomalous
The RWKV state is the memory of the entire flow history — no quadratic attention needed.


Packet 1 arrives:
  tokens [DIR_C2S, LEN_28, DT_0, TTL_4, TCP, SP_11, DP_16, ACK, SEP]
  → model.step() × 9 → state_1  (RWKV remembers pkt1)

Packet 2 arrives (1ms later):
  tokens [DIR_C2S, LEN_28, DT_1, ...]
  → model.step() × 9 → state_2  (remembers pkt1+pkt2)

...

Packet 500 arrives:
  → model.step() × 9 → state_500
  → NLL spike detected → alert raised
Why This Matters for Your Paper
Design choice	What it proves
Scapy extracts only header fields	Gap 1: Model literally cannot see payload — DPI-free by design
9 tokens × N packets per flow	Gap 2: Real flows produce 38–1,154 tokens — SSM O(T) advantage measurable
model.step() per token	Streaming inference — one RWKV state per flow, O(1) memory
PAD masking in loss	Variable-length flows handled correctly — no information leak
Perplexity = anomaly score	Unsupervised detection — no labels needed at inference time
